The most common uses of serial ports are either for communications between two computers (directly or over a modem) or to attach a serial peripheral, such as a serial mouse.  The Serial Port Device Driver only provides support for the actual serial port hardware.  In order to make use of the port, additional device drivers and software are needed.\
\
If you will be using a serial mouse on a serial port which is controlled by the Serial Port Device Driver, then configure the Serial Mouse Device Driver as well.\
\
In order to allow application programs access to any serial ports controlled by the Serial Port Device Driver, you must configure the 
\fc0\cf0 TTY Port Server Device Driver.  This driver provides the UNIX TTY layer and creates device nodes for all configured serial ports.  All popular UNIX and OPENSTEP for Mach communication software uses the TTY layer, including NXFax, UUCP, Taylor UUCP, PPP, and tip.\

\fc1\cf1 \
In order to use the Serial Port Device Driver with PCMCIA devices, you need to configure two additional device drivers.  The PCMCIA Bus Support Device Driver provides kernel support for PCMCIA features.  You also need the device driver for the PCMCIA socket adapter, such as the 
\fc0\cf0 Intel 82365 PCMCIA Adapter Device Driver, which supports most built-in and many add-on PCMCIA socket adapters.
\fc1\cf1 \
