\b\fc0\cf0 \

\fc1\cf1 Using PCMCIA Modems
\fc0\cf0 \

\b0 \
There are a few special considerations you need to be aware of when using PCMCIA devices.  OPENSTEP for Mach 4.0 does not support hot-swapping, so you should never insert or remove a PCMCIA device while the machine is running.\
\

\b\fi-1080\li1440 Warning:	
\b0 Inserting or removing a PCMCIA device while the system is running may result in OPENSTEP for Mach hanging or crashing.  It may also damage the PCMCIA device or socket if either doesn't support hot-swapping.\
\

\fi0\li360 For PCMCIA devices, the Port Address and IRQ Level settings must be within the abilities of the PCMCIA device as well as the PCMCIA adapter it is inserted into.  Generally, any available IRQ Level may be chosen, though choosing a Port Address that isn't one of the standard COM addresses may not work.  NeXT recommends choosing one of the four standard COM Port Addresses, first making sure that no serial ports on your system board are enabled at that same address.\
\
For more information, see the "Troubleshooting" section under the help topic "Hardware Details".\
\
It is recommended that any PCMCIA serial device drivers be configured last, as you may choose to boot the system with or without the PCMCIA modem inserted.  Serial ports will be probed in the order in which they are numbered in Configure's Other Devices list, and the presence or absence of a serial port in the middle of the list will effect the device node names assigned to subsequent ports.  For more information, see Configure's on-line help for the TTY Port Server Device Driver.\

